In our editorial, we will probably continue to debate for a long time about whether this was a black-out of the game makers or whether the authors consider us so foolish.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is quite attractive in most cases and here and there even brilliant.
The more annoying is that in some exciting moments the image recovery frequency becomes slower and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
This, however, applies primarily to accidents with a greater number of participants, where a continuous FPS does not benefit anyway.
The sound is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an attempt to address a as wide as possible scale rather young audience, a soundtrack a lá "from everyone something" emerged - but who purchases such a game already because of music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? the feelings are rather mixed.
If the game wasn’t shattered by the mentioned completely unnecessary errors, we would have been able to claim with the brust of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But so the game seems somehow unfinished.
A class of pleasure for itself, but you should be prepared to put those errors into your eyes with the power of airport lamps.
