IBM History: From Cash Cutting to Space Flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded a hundred years ago in New York, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM took it only in 1924 – originally it was a brand name for a headquarters in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the subsequent company IBM was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies such as the famous card clocks to register the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who was the chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who appointed the head of the competitive company Thomas J. Watson to help him lead the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shadow - on Watson's ideas is based to date the unbeatable culture and identity of the company.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the manufacturing and distribution of all possible machines for trade - from rubber and cash cutting machines to cash.
In the first four decades in which Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he was sitting in the chief chair for forty years, only then he was dissolved by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA guide flights into the universe - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture, the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that set the computer standard of that time came to market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the past three years is the concept of “Smart Planet”.
It constitutes the intention of smartly deploying technologies in unplanned areas, for example in order to improve the situation in the transport and urban administration.
In the trading sector, IBM recently launched the “Smart Commerce” platform, which aims to help traders lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932, IBM founded its headquarters in Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brünn.
The Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a top world-class research team that deals with voice recognition technology.
