Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorized state travel agencies in the then Czech Republic: Čedok, Sportturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At that time the travel agencies sold only travel to the socialist eastern bloc countries, in the West only selected people were allowed.
And so, Czech tourists travel to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (Sotschi on the Crimea Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia introduced a pro-west course and therefore the travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
One great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not allowed even to the citizens of the Eastern Block (thus also to the Czechoslovak) to travel freely within the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the USSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
At that time the travel agencies also offered to travel to the West, but then they had to buy enormous serpents or even stay in the sleep bag before the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
It was also not so long.
The so-called currency use - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchanged currency, so without the use of the currency it would have been impossible to provide the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The most Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dats - a habit that lasts until today.
The gathered revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the DDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is the fact that you could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czechs—Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the Yugoslavia at the time.
Just from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation to the neighboring Western European countries was abolished, causing a huge wave of short visits especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechs could not get enough from their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
Thus, the Czech travellers slept in the telt in the park when they traveled to Paris, because who had already had the money for a hotel or a pension at that time.
A typical feature of foreign trips of the Czechs at that time was a packed bag room with conservances, beer and durable roast, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangable Czech crown – after decades, our tourists could finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our living level and thus also the average salary increased, which in 1997 led to another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to regularly prepare charter flights after 1997, making the flights incredibly cool, thanks to the possibility of trading quantities, compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already undue payment transactions with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of the “post-samination” travel traffic came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand the first direct charter flight was made to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly annually to remote sunny countries; this year, 12 exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
The 100 Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the era that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US lifted the visa obligation for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the highly developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs for the first time spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 CZK per person for a single holiday stay including the cost of the holiday site.
