Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who claimed to have committed a bullying in Norway in July in which 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing before the court.
Although Breivik may have handled alone, he is far from alone in the cyberspace: he has spent a lot of time until his attack in front of his computer and chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support extreme-right groups on the sides of social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It’s easy – you just need to log in to Facebook.
“We found it was not difficult to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the chief author of a recent report by the British Idea Factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says that researchers simply have to use the advertising tool of the page to determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - as marketers have done for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of extreme-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with adds, but instead of linking to a new band or a new diet product, the adds invited users to a survey that asked about their educational status, their attitude to violence and their own future assessment.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and colleagues were able to interrogate more than 10,000 supporters from 14 extreme-right parties in 11 European countries – without having to leave their office once.
“It’s a fairly new method of research,” says Bartlett.
Some of the results hardly surprise. online supporters of extreme right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
“Those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just an example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factory, medical researchers and policy scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as in "Likes", text news and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content a day, Facebook’s “Datensupernova” generates a research boom that has made the number of scientific work with the name of this page in the title increase by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this page you can study people that you usually do not reach with your clipboard on the street.
“When you tried to question people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“They had to inform the party first and it would never give them access,” says Bartlett.
“In Facebook, it’s all gone – you’re going straight to them.”
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and colleagues found that students who discussed their full-rush on Facebook were significantly more likely to be problematic than students who silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that equal students, such as residential consultants, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you don’t recognize it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Morenos co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle to the Washington Post.
“We have found a way to identify threatened children that would not have been found otherwise.”
Facebook is also constantly accessing the data of its own population.
The data team of the site has created statistics about the relationship status and Valentine's Day, electoral participation in the 2010 interim elections and a National Happiness Index (which primarily used data that only Facebook has access to - Masters of Digital Freedom have long known that the site should make its large database available to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the page is watching them whether they want it or not. To be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you allow the page to bring out your own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know anything about?
While researchers have strictly defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online everything is permitted.
"I don't think that many users have ever thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he explored the public pages of students on Facebook.
“It was just about her and her friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a researcher is absolutely honest.
