Climate Disadvantages Boost the Economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in the government, unemployment and black labour increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investments dropped and the economy stagnated.
2011 will remain in memory in the economic history of Sinaloas. It is the first year when Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and shed great hopes regarding economic growth, is at the government. However, as a result of climate contradictions, growth cannot be spoken, but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators have deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of losses in agriculture, but also closed the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 per cent in the first quarter of the year.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (so-called the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frozen, 582,000 hectares of agriculture land have been damaged, of which 78,03 percent have been completely destroyed and the remaining 21,07 percent have been partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has led the unemployment to continuously rise in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografia observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, since from January to March 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloas had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 per cent of the occupational population. In the second quarter the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 per cent and from July to September to 6.19 per cent, resulting in 74.000 unemployment in Sinaloa. This is 18 969 people more than in the first quarter of the year.
Lower liquidity
The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented, the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, among other things with liquidity losses on the market as a result of the funds cut by the legislation that was adopted to fight money laundering in Congress, because for those who prohibitedly buy dollars, it's not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for something else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has dropped. this is due to the problem of entry and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and look for work here, which causes unemployment to rise,” he says.
The black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if we take into account the high percentage of black labour, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38 percent of the workers in the country who work without paying in the social insurance funds.
Unemployment and black labour are the lowest wages in all of Mexico, according to statistics by the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Mexican Government Agency for Labour and Social Care).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 Pesos until September; this is much less than the national average, which is at 7375 Pesos.
The decline of ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the growing unemployment, in 2011 the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) is recorded in the last ten years. According to Secretaría de Economía (state economic authority), the ADI was from January to June 630 597 dollars, which is a swing of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development) recorded a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, primarily from companies from the third-party sector.
The debt
In light of the economic crisis, the state government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to the National Congress in July, which should be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy.
Reactions
For the representatives of the entrepreneurship the first year of government made Mario López Valdés government inability obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of the Processing Industry in Mexico) said that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of the various sectors, including the state government.
“The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very thin this year. it has to be hard to work to recover the lost land this year and in 2012 we have to double our efforts. the efforts of all and in particular the progress of the already well-defined government team have not been sufficiently agreed with each other,” he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said events such as the cold at the beginning of the year complicated and slowed the country’s economic development.
“The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frozen. One of the main impacts is a slowed economy that is not moving enough to trigger an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services.
Re-defining the appeal
Theodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Commercial Association of Mexico) in Sinaloa, said it is necessary to drive the state to more dynamic productive activities.
We believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program to re-definit the economic appeal and line of the country, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources of Sinaloas,” he said.
There is a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex emphasized the importance of developing a future perspective that will lead the government’s efforts to better routes.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in different areas. economic development has advanced, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he explained.
He emphasized that the current state power has made progress with the government.
“There are areas that can be said that the government has acted more comprehensive. what I can say is that it has been worked and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it,” he said.
