The court approves the transition to digital television in Mexico for 2015
The conversion of analog to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional claims submitted by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, and in accordance with which the transition of analogues to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 must be passed, due to the lack of eight votes required to object to the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, was the opinion that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the law decree with the details on the transition to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate because it did not receive the necessary qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality.
In the proposal for the complaint, which was drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the legislative decree unconstitutional, as for which the radio and television regulations are responsible for the Commission Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), therefore the legislative decree would be contrary to the hierarchical principles and the legislative provisions.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument both the Senate and the House of Representatives raised constitutional complaints against the bill. After the complaints were accepted, the Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied to the bill and introduced all activities to establish the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the appeal submitted by the House of Representatives, without participating in the debate on the project, for which also the Minister Sánchez Cordero was responsible.
In his post, the Prime Minister stated not to agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the country government cannot regulate by general regulations the measures that the public administration is intended to take.
"I also don't think that if you do so, it would affect the independence of the regulatory body." she also reminded that for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, the central state government is responsible, because it is the head of state affairs.
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have occurred throughout the world in recent years, and it leads to a better use of the radio spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The suspension of the transformation, she said, is a suspension of the use of digitalization, which is a decision in public interest, which has not only technical aspects, "because it covers economic, social, political and security technical aspects."
These matters, she emphasized, "have made the action of the entire system necessary, in accordance with the principle of economic leadership by the state they contained a group of characteristics that put the constitution in the hands of the central state government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already undertaken the digital transformation through the government, although they had highly specialized facilities.
"It cannot be concluded that the government would interfere in Congress' competences by issuing the contested law decree because the laws adopted by the legislative would be respected," she said.
The possibility of counting the voting cards in Michoacán individually is considered
According to PREP, the difference between the first and the second place in the election of the Governor is about 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 still not elected.
The possibility of the individual counting of the votes is a reality this year at the Michoacán elections, since according to the data issued by the Program de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the governor's elections is about 27 percent, with 879 votes from a total of 6074 still not counted.
In this regard, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, reminded that just last November 9 the Electoral Bureau had adopted a series of arrangements to harmonise local regulations with the federal reforms in electoral matters.
It should be remembered that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by Congress so that they had not entered into force during this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel refused to publish it in the state declaration within the deadlines set forth with the argument, neither having objection to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional draft submitted by the local legislative and judged the prosecutor's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and unlawful" as he has no right to "decision or veto against it."
María de los Ángeles Llanderal said in an interview on the possibility of the individual counting of the votes that thanks to the adoption of the directives by the Consejo General del IEM now there is the possibility that the local electoral authority can count the voting numbers partially or entirely.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted The results in the protocols do not agree; the protocol on the counting and calculation of the votes is not present or is not in possession of the chairman of the voting committee or there are obvious errors or changes in the protocols.
Furthermore, the total calculation of the fully completed election scenes can take place if there is a difference between the suspected winner and the second place, which is equal or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting is present an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the listed candidates.
The vote count can also be made in its entirety if, after completion of the regular calculation, the difference between the suspected winner and the candidate on the second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that an explicit request is presented by a representative of the party whose candidate has become the second.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and second places is just 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
