The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their twentieth anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On that day, they will appear at the National Stadium at 19.30 p.m. together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You will read an extract from the conversation, the full copy of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rica fans, a dream is realised when Pearl Jam is playing in Costa Rica: Are you aware what it means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is realised for us too.
This is just the second time we play in South and Central America, and so far it has been great.
It’s so beautiful country that we’ll definitely stay there for a few days.
It is exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely abandoned. they experience the days before the concert more intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being on our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to come to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long to come here.
Some people even think your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Is this not a bit of pressure from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve made in the last 21 years took place in the last two weeks.
We played on a few giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and are enthusiastic about the jungle. for this Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always been driving to surf to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. together with Mexico are the great areas to surf. in this way, about people who love surfing, we have learned about it.
With a look at the tour, you have offered giant shows with many songs.
What plans do you have for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there, we don’t put any boundaries.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why ?
I think this is partly because we have nine albums and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so the decision we’re going to play each does not fall easily.
If we take in the repertoire two or three songs that we have not played for a long time, we can keep our concentration better and they surprise us because they call us the reasons why we liked these songs.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think, therefore also for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yes and total.
First of all, I think that no one of us has imagined to play once in a great rock band, and that’s still over 20 years.
We continue to put on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We love each other and are excited to produce music.
We are lucky to be able to travel to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things could not be better.
What did it mean for you to have participated actively in the Grunge’s birthday hour?
It has always been an honor to be a member of this group of big bands.
We are well friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement arises from a group of friends.
Sometimes a band comes out of a city, but it’s unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
