Asphalt from the UNAM prevents clashes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the UNAM University of Mexico, has developed polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations.
If attention was paid to the signs that arise from the road cover, it would not be necessary to repair 200,000 shock holes if the rain time in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (Mexico Valley City Area) breaks out, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning and assured that if the extraction and maintenance of the asphalt cover is done properly, the number of shock holes will be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Strailer from a technical point of view", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops polymer-modified asphalt to produce an asphalt-like mixture, which, however, has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road cover and thus prevent the appearance of shock blows.
He explained that the asphalt - the hardest part of oil - is a carbon hydrogen compound, of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes.
The asphaltic behavior means that the asphaltic behavior at high temperatures of almost 180°C acts like a fluid, at 120°C it is very fluid and at 50°C it is almost solid, while it becomes broken at very low temperatures.
“This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the streets is not uniform, but changes one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations,” the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly had a flexible road load consisting of six material layers, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the upper layers is a sliding layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalted and then fixed stones.
Each stone of this layer is covered in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer enables a good power distribution in the road load.
“If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed,” the chemical engineer said.
“Over the loading layer,” he said, “there is a last layer, the so-called loading layer, which consists of small stones, i.e. of sand, which was also wrapped in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the welding layer and they need to produce irritation.
The road load receives and distributes the most of the strengths, the cargo layer also requires an adequate thickness and the material from which it consists must be kept.
The weather conditions, especially moisture and temperature fluctuations, are other, important factors to be taken into account, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the dust layer.
When the ground becomes wet, water penetrates into the layer and only difficult to get out again. This causes a deviation of all layers of the road cover and consequently the appearance of shock holes.
When a hole occurs," he said, "the roof layer will first be dropped, while the slurry layer will only be damaged afterwards. but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be kept up with the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of shock holes. therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road cover must always be in proportion to the vehicle load and it must be guaranteed that this regulation is followed in order to avoid frequent shock holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many further research work was left to wait, for example on asphalt emulsions that were already on the market in other countries, and with which the slopes could be repaired easily and without the application of high temperatures.
